Introduction

Chess is a puzzle game where you can compete one-on-one with your opponent. In general, it can become harshly competitive and fun enough where other people will be motivated to play this game. This examination is about how each of the players position affects their performance and which class are they played best.

Example:

Boxplot Diagram

another example using snipe

Link to your data

The R project webpage, all found in kaggle: https://www.kaggle.com/arevel/chess-games

Questions/ Reasons

If you are a chess player, will you face end up in either a normal termination or penalties? Which side (Black or White) tends to have its skill rate or rating difference to reach to its own termination? Does this also depend if you are an experienced chess player or not?

Visualizations

table(chessGames2$Result)
## 
##       *     0-1     1-0 1/2-1/2 
##    1343 2902394 3113572  238875
reorder_size <- function(x) {
        factor(x, levels = names(sort(table(x), decreasing = TRUE)[1:10]))
}


chessGames2 %>%
   filter(!is.na(reorder_size(White))) %>%
     ggplot(aes(x= White, fill=White)) + 
        geom_bar() +xlab("Top 10 White Players")+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

chessGames2 %>%
   filter(!is.na(reorder_size(Black))) %>%
     ggplot(aes(x= Black, fill=Black)) + 
        geom_bar() + xlab("Top 10 Black Players")+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

chessGames2 %>%
   filter(!is.na(reorder_size(Opening))) %>%
     ggplot(aes(x= Opening, fill=Opening)) + 
        geom_bar() +xlab("Top 10 Initial Moves Used")+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

skillCheckWhite1 = ifelse(chessGames2$WhiteEloRate < 1000, "Newcomer", 
                  ifelse(chessGames2$WhiteEloRate < 1200, "Class E",
                  ifelse(chessGames2$WhiteEloRate < 1400, "Class D",
                  ifelse(chessGames2$WhiteEloRate < 1600, "Class C", 
                  ifelse(chessGames2$WhiteEloRate < 1800, "Class B", 
                  ifelse(chessGames2$WhiteEloRate < 2000, "Class A", 
                  ifelse(chessGames2$WhiteEloRate < 2200, "Expert",
                  ifelse(chessGames2$WhiteEloRate > 2400, "Senior Master","Master"))))))))
                  
skillCheckWhite2 = factor(skillCheckWhite1,

chessGames3 <- chessGames2 %>% mutate(newTermination = as.factor(ifelse(Termination == "Normal", "Normal", "Penalty")))
chessGamesExpW <- chessGames2 %>% mutate(ExpertOrNot = as.factor(ifelse(WhiteEloRate >= 2200, "Expert", "Amateur")))
chessGamesExpB <- chessGames2 %>% mutate(ExpertOrNot = as.factor(ifelse(WhiteEloRate >= 2200, "Expert", "Amateur")))
set.seed(88)
split <- sample.split(chessGames3$newTermination, SplitRatio = 0.00001)

cglTrain <- subset(chessGames3, split == TRUE)

chessGameLog <- glm(newTermination ~ WhiteRatingDifference+BlackRatingDifference+WhiteEloRate+BlackEloRate, data= cglTrain ,family=binomial)
summary(chessGameLog)

Conclusions

As far as this study has been observed, both Elo rates from both sides appear to approach to 0 if they tend to belong in a higher class. Otherwise, the lower class tend to have a higher difference. Additionally, the Black side seems to have a higher specificity and lower sensitivity than the White side since it has a smaller threshold of 0.95 and the White side has a perfect classifier which means it has a higher true positive rate and the area under the curve is higher.
